==Middle English==
===Etymology 1===
From {{der|enm|ang|ġif}}.
====Conjunction====
{{head|enm|conjunction}}
# [[if]]
#* '''c. 1438''', [[w:John Lydgate|John Lydgate]] ''Fall of Princes'':
#*: '''Yiff''' ther was lak, thou woldest crie & pleyne.
#* '''c. 1438''', [[w:John Lydgate|John Lydgate]] ''Fall of Princes'':
#*: And '''yiff''' that trust with pryncis wil nat tarie,<br />Litil merueile thouh the peeple varie {{...}}
#* {{quote-book|enm|author={{w|Geoffrey Chaucer}}|title=Legend of Good Women|year=c. 1385-1386|passage={{...}} That '''yiff''' that god that hevene and erthe made<br />Wolde haue a love For beaute and goodness<br />And womanhede and trouthe and semelynesse […]}}
===Etymology 2===
From {{der|enm|ang|giefan}}.
====Verb====
{{head|enm|verb}}
# {{alternative form of|enm|yiven}}
#* '''1393''', [[w:Jean d'Arras|Jean d’Arras]] ''Roman de Melusine'':
#*: Another ordre to you '''yiff''' I shall,<br />A knyght will you mak of full hye degre<br />As your brethren ben named ryght roiall.
